<subSubSection id="C343D49AFFC2FFFEFD5081697C67A2CD" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BE68711FFC2FFFEFD5081697C67A2CD" blockId="8.[707,1194,194,693]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis id="B92D5B03FFC2FFFEFD5081697C59A26E" bold="true" box="[731,845,513,534]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a patronym honoring Mr. Edward G. Riley, entomology collection manager at 
<collectingRegion id="499D49F3FFC2FFFEFC00815E7CD0A233" box="[907,964,566,587]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">Texas</collectingRegion>
A&amp;M University and specialist on the 
<taxonomicName id="4C59FC92FFC2FFFEFCE081397CEBA21E" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[875,1023,593,614]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="529" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysomelidae</taxonomicName>
. He was the first to notice the distinctiveness of the unusual specimen, designated herein as 
<typeStatus id="54E239B3FFC2FFFEFC6981EE7B2BA2E3" box="[994,1087,646,667]" pageId="8" pageNumber="529">holotype</typeStatus>
, from the TAMU collection.
</paragraph>
